    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. i'm not sure if it's just aging though because it seems pretty widespread across all my plants. i read somewhere about nitrogen deficiency making the bottom leaves go yellow like that. do you think that could be it? and if so, how do i fix the soil pH to help with that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Nitrogen deficiency is a strong possibility, especially if the yellowing is widespread, as it causes the plant to recycle nitrogen from older leaves to fuel new growth. To fix this, you can apply a balanced fertilizer or one high in nitrogen, but correcting soil pH is a separate issue that requires adding lime to raise acidity or sulfur to lower it. Since improper pH can also block nutrient uptake, a soil test is the most reliable way to determine your exact needs before applying amendments. If your soil is too acidic, adding lime will help, but be sure to do this gradually to avoid shocking your plants.",
      "source": "target",
